# RDP Detection Validation Script
# Target: xsiamclient02
# Purpose: Generate telemetry for XDR validation

$target = ""
$testUser = "SimulatedAttacker"
$iterations = 5 # Small number for validation; avoids account lockout

Write-Host "Starting RDP validation telemetry generation for $target..." -ForegroundColor Cyan

for ($i = 1; $i -le $iterations; $i++) {
    Write-Host "Attempt $i: Initiating RDP connection signal..." -ForegroundColor Yellow
    
    # 1. Simulates the process activity (mstsc.exe)
    # 2. Generates the network connection attempt to port 3389
    # Using 'cmdkey' allows the script to pass a "bad" credential without a GUI popup
    cmdkey /add:$target /user:$testUser /pass:"WrongPassword$i"
    
    # Start the RDP process (it will fail authentication silently or show a prompt)
    Start-Process mstsc.exe -ArgumentList "/v:$target" -WindowStyle Hidden
    
    # Brief pause to allow the agent to capture the session start
    Start-Sleep -Seconds 3
    
    # Clean up the process and the cached "bad" credential
    Stop-Process -Name mstsc -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
    cmdkey /delete:$target
}

Write-Host "Validation complete. Check XSIAM for Event ID 4625 and mstsc.exe activity." -ForegroundColor Green

title: Feels footsteps through floor
content:
‚ÄúYou both stay here,‚Äù said Vashta, ‚Äúwhile I try to salvage the situation
out there, and engineer a way for you to continue your investigation!‚Äù

‚ÄúUnderstood, ma‚Äôam,‚Äù said Ana.

With one last glare, Vashta turned, flung open the door, charged
through, and slammed it behind her.

[...]

To my surprise, her grin didn‚Äôt flicker one jot. ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs not entirely true,
either.‚Äù

‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs not? That it was the Hazas, or that your assistant was killed?‚Äù
‚ÄúFocus, Din. We are here to figure out how this calamity happened and
who is responsible. Follow that thread, and that thread alone, and we shall
have victory.‚Äù Then she cocked her head, knelt, and felt the fretvine floor.
‚ÄúVashta is coming back. I can feel her stride in the very wood‚Ä¶ And I think
Miljin and Strovi are with her. Come. Let us pretend to be professional, you
and I, for hell and the gentry await.‚Äù

‚ÄúHERE,‚Äù SAID VASHTA coldly, ‚Äúis what I have been able to salvage. First,
Fayazi Haza does not wish to be in the room with you anymore, Immunis.
To have made such an attack on her character during such a period of grief
is beyond toleration. Is that clear?‚Äù

Ana shrugged. ‚ÄúThat is clear if not welcome, ma‚Äôam.‚Äù

- The Tainted Cup, Chapter 25 pgs. 219 & 222

title: Reads desk where letter was written
content:
‚ÄúI can‚Äôt find a damn thing,‚Äù said Kalista around her pipe. Her breath
shivered with smoke as she spoke. ‚ÄúThis is a professional, surely. They
removed everything of note. From the look of it, I almost doubt if Suberek
knew how to write.‚Äù

Ana rocked forward, her hands still probing the workshop table. ‚ÄúNo,‚Äù
she said softly. ‚ÄúHe knew how to write. And he did a lot of it right here.‚Äù
There was a long silence as everyone turned to look at her, her hands
placed on the slab of wood like a reedwitch telling fortunes at a canton fair.

‚ÄúYou‚Ä¶‚Äù Kalista laughed, incredulous. ‚ÄúYou aren‚Äôt suggesting you
can‚Ä¶You can, what, feel what was written there?‚Äù

‚ÄúI can feel many things,‚Äù said Ana quietly. ‚ÄúHe was a very hard writer,
you see. Pressed his ashpen with tremendous force‚Ä¶The tricky thing is
identifying what was recent.‚Äù Her index finger paused on one spot of the
scarred table. ‚ÄúHere, for example‚Ä¶Wrote down an order for two panels‚Ä¶
Dated sometime in the month of Hajnal. I think. Tricky to read this‚Ä¶‚Äù
Uhad looked to Nusis. ‚ÄúIs this really possible?‚Äù

‚ÄúOf course,‚Äù said Nusis. ‚ÄúI know some sensitivity grafts help sculptors
and surgeons find the weaknesses in many materials.‚Äù

‚ÄúIf we get a length of ashpen,‚Äù said Ana, ‚Äúand a sheet of thin fernpaper,
I can discover more.‚Äù

- The Tainted Cup, Chapter 22 pg. 197

title: Reads city's construction orders in three hours
content:
I looked down. Ana was lying on the floor on her back at Strovi‚Äôs feet,
half-concealed in a pile of parchments, blindfolded as usual. To her left was
a tray containing the remains of a fish, salted and piled with herbs, the flesh
so pink it must have never known flame.

[...]

‚ÄúHe‚Äôs just brought you your orders, ma‚Äôam?‚Äù I asked. ‚ÄúFrom the shape
of things, he‚Äôs been here awhile. You‚Äôve been interrogating him, haven‚Äôt
you.‚Äù

‚ÄúIt, ah‚Ä¶‚Äù Strovi cleared his throat. ‚ÄúIt has been an hour or so, ma‚Äôam.
Possibly two. Or, ah, three.‚Äù

Ana waved a hand, indifferent. ‚ÄúPossibly. It‚Äôs not very often that I get to
parley with a Talagray Legion officer.‚Äù

[...]

We possibly have a who. Kind of think we have a how‚Äî--for, presumably, 
Jolgalgan came to one of these secret meetings of Engineers and poisoned them 
all there. And thanks to your and Miljin‚Äôs work yesterday, Din, we also have a when
---the Engineers were poisoned eight days before the breach, the date of their last
meeting, the sixth of Kyuz. Now we just need the where. And Strovi here has already 
given us the materials we need to solve the rest!‚Äù 

She turned her blindfolded face to him. 

‚ÄúThese orders are from every fernpaper miller in the city, correct, Captain?‚Äù

‚ÄúYes, ma‚Äôam,‚Äù said Strovi. ‚ÄúAll we could find.‚Äù

‚ÄúAnd we‚Äôre looking for big orders. All conducted on or about eight days
before the breach‚Äîthe day of the poisoning.‚Äù She pursed her mouth,
chewing on an especially tough piece of gristle, then said, ‚ÄúThere are, I
think, four options.‚Äù

Strovi looked startled. ‚ÄúY-you‚Äôve already read them all, ma‚Äôam?‚Äù

‚ÄúOur conversation was interesting, Captain,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúBut not so
interesting as to occupy the whole of my attention‚Ä¶‚Äù Still blindfolded, she
snatched up four different papers, walked over on her knees, fumbled to
find Strovi‚Äôs legs, and then stuffed the papers into his lap. Then she leaned
forward to search the top one with her fingers until she pointed to a line.
‚ÄúThis mill here‚ÄîOstrok‚Äôs? See it? Order for four panels, nine days before
the breach.‚Äù

- The Tainted Cup, Chapter 19 pgs. 171-174

title: Feels weather through floor
content:
‚ÄúWhy are you‚Ä¶‚Äù I said.

‚ÄúOn the floor?‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúI can feel the movements of this tower better
from here, Din, reading the wind and the weather with my back.‚Äù She
grinned. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs marvelous. You ought to try it sometime.‚Äù

- The Tainted Cup, Chapter 19 pg. 171

title: ffix_playthrough
content:
Final Fantasy IX mostly complete playthrough

Goals:
- See as much content as possible
- Get most unique items 
- Do as many sidequests as possible
- Become the Tetra Master
- Encounter most/all monsters
- Defeat Ozma, which I've never done

Using the following mods:
- ATB mod. Ups the frame rate, speeds up battle intro, and changes the ATB system. We'll see if this is good or not, if it's bad we'll flush it, but we'll probably keep it (https://www.romhacking.net/hacks/9029/)
- Toggle encounters on/off. Generally I'll clear an area first before I allow doing this, exceptions include world map
- Excalibur II 500 hour patch. I'd be fine without the weapon, but why not. An alternative to keeping your game on for 2.25 years to overflow the clock

I'm playing the PSX version. It's on emulator. Don't be annoying about it. Some timing games like jump rope and nobles might not be happening (especially on emu), I'm washed

This is ultimately a replay but it's been a very long time since I've really dug deep into this game. This time I want to play a little more thoroughly with some informed gameplay, like managing stats (https://web.archive.org/web/20250501000000*/http://letao.is-a-geek.net/ff9stats/), but nothing too crazy. It's for fun. I'll definitely miss some random things, who cares. 

Let's play some cards
